There were triumviri —tresviri‚ often written with a numeral IIIviri, is, perhaps, the more correct term—for various purposes ordinary and extraordinary. The tresviri capitales were charged with the order of the streets in Rome, and performed, in addition, some of the functions of our sheriffs. These were permanent officials. T resviri coloniae deducendae or agro dividunde, on the other hand, were appointed for the temporary purpose which their title indicated.
